1   April 1 Cadets called to man portions of Richmond defensive lines  1865 April  Corps disbanded on April 2 at the Alms House  on eve of evacuation of Richmond by Confederate Forces  each cadet found his way home or elsewhere as best he could  A considerable number of them followed the canal to Columbia  Fluvanna County  and dispersed there  Gen  Robert E  Lee surrendered at Appomattox on April 9  1865 October 17 VMI reopened in Lexington  Academic work resumed just 6 months after the end of the war 1859 November A contingent of the Corps was dispatched to Charles Town following John Brown s raid on the Harper s Ferry arsenal  Cadets stood guard at Brown s execution on December 2 1859 November  A contingent of the Corps was dispatched 1861 April The Corps was sent to Richmond  where cadets drilled Confederate army recruits  The commanding officer during this trip was Major Thomas J   Stonewall  Jackson  who had joined VMI s faculty in 1851 as professor of natural and experimental philosophy and instructor of artillery  Jackson accepted a commission and left for active duty soon after the Corps arrived in Richmond 1861 April  Major Thomas J   Stonewall  Jackson 1861 July 4 The Class of 1861 was graduated as of this date 1861 July 4  1861 December 6 The Class of 1862 was graduated as of this date 1861 December 6  1862 January 1 The Institute reopened in Lexington  Cadets who would have been First Classmen had graduated early and were already serving in the military 1862 January 1  1862 May The Corps was ordered to aid General Jackson s forces during the McDowell campaign  The cadets  commanded by Scott Shipp  marched in pursuit of Federal troops but were not engaged in battle 1862 May  1863 May General Stonewall Jackson died on May 10 from wounds received at the Battle of Chancellorsville  and his body was returned to Lexington for burial 1863 May  General Stonewall Jackson died 1863 August December The Corps was called into the field to defend against the raids of General William Averell  but were not engaged in battle 1863 August December  1864 May 15 The Battle of New Market  The Corps  again under the command of Scott Shipp  marched into battle along with General John C  Breckinridge s forces against Federal troops led by General Franz Sigel  Ten cadets were mortally wounded 1864 May 15  The Battle of New Market  1864 June 11 Federal troops  under the command of General David Hunter  entered Lexington  The Corps retreated to a camp in the Blue Ridge near Balcony Falls  VMI was burned the next day by Hunter s soldiers  On June 25 the Corps returned to Lexington  only to be furloughed two days later 1864 June 11  Federal troops  under the command of General David Hunter 1864 October 1 Corps assembled at Camp Lee  near Richmond  VA  Engaged in military duties in trenches around Richmond  but no academic work took place 1864 October 1  1864 October 27 Corps encamped at Poe s Farm as infantry support for nearby battery  comprised part of the Confederate Forces of the Department of Richmond 1864 October 27  1864 December 12 Moved from Poe s Farm to Alms House  Richmond  some cadets granted 10 day furlough to procure clothing and supplies 1864 December 12  1864 December 28 Academic work resumed at the Alms House in Richmond  VMI s temporary headquarters 1864 December 28  1864 March 11   April 1 Cadets called to man portions of Richmond defensive lines 1864 March 11   April 1  1865 April  Corps disbanded on April 2 at the Alms House  on eve of evacuation of Richmond by Confederate Forces  each cadet found his way home or elsewhere as best he could  A considerable number of them followed the canal to Columbia  Fluvanna County  and dispersed there  Gen  Robert E  Lee surrendered at Appomattox on April 9 1865 April 1865 October 17 VMI reopened in Lexington  Academic work resumed just 6 months after the end of the war 1865 October 17  VMI Foundation Keydet Club Alumni Webcams Directories My VMI VMI Foundation Keydet Club Alumni VMI Fo